\" Approach\\\\nIf your \\\\\\\"override\\\\\\\" involves complex HTML rather than just a string of text, you can pass a rendered block or another template as a variable.\\\\n\\\\n**1. The Main Template:**\\\\n```html\\\\n{% include \\\\\\\"_card.html\\\\\\\" with title\\\\u003d\\\\\\\"Complex Card\\\\\\\" content\\\\u003dspecial_html_variable %}\\\\n```\\\\n*Note: This requires you to pass the HTML from your view or a custom template tag.*\\\\n\\\\n---\\\\n\\\\n### Method 3: Using `django-overextends` or Custom Tags\\\\nIf you find yourself wishing `include` worked exactly like `extends` (where you can define blocks), the native DTL doesn't support it. However, many developers use **Jinja2** (which Django supports) because it allows for **Macros**, which are much more flexible for this specific use case.\\\\n\\\\n#### Comparison of Include vs. Extend\\\\n\\\\n| Feature | `{% extends %}` |\\\"],null,null,null,null,true,null,[1],\\\"en\\\",null,null,[null,null,null,null,null,null,[0],[]],null,null,true,null,null,null,null,null,[false],null,false,[],null,null,null,[]]],[\\\"California, USA\\\",\\\"SWML_DESCRIPTION_FROM_YOUR_INTERNET_ADDRESS\\\",false,null,\\\"//www.google.com/maps/vt/data\\\\u003d7KRMCtKULmfFRNc3txH4F9VXgNSb6CwFMH3PVINz9PlUGdvRefP07Ws23u29o0ckUnlZKkL7FSkcM2-yc6OQriBOChui0d-GN9f1CsaShmquHeBPYmLVdqoFfzWrWKsis9lSq8B_deKaHIp1MVA8HX1vF6rOpIAmolKLp32GjEodsRCWDwaFvdop7A\\\"],null,null,\\\"US\\\",null,null,null,null,null,false,null,null,null,null,\\\"en\\\",null,null,null,true,[null,[false,false],[false]],null,[[[[null,[null,0,\\\"In the standard Django Template Language (DTL), the {% include %} tag is designed for reusability, not extensibility. This means that unlike {% extends %}, you cannot use {% block %} tags inside an included file and expect to \\\\\\\"override\\\\\\\" them from the parent template.\\\",[[52,65,[[null,null,null,null,3]]],[86,97,[[null,null,null,null,2]]],[103,116,[[null,null,null,null,2]]],[141,154,[[null,null,null,null,3]]],[171,182,